	<p>
	This IPA keyboard allows you to type pronunciations of English words as th=
ey
	appear in major English dictionaries from publishers like Longman, Oxford,=
 etc.
	Dictionary transcriptions are =E2=80=9Cphonemic transcriptions=E2=80=9D. T=
hey only give you the broad-strokes view of the pronunciation
	=E2=80=93 just enough to make sure you won=E2=80=99t confuse two different=
 words.
	If you need to represent precise sound qualities (for example, the differe=
nt quality of <span class=3D"char">p</span> in
	<i>pot</i> vs. <i>spot</i>) or differences between accents of English,
	use the <a href=3D"https://ipa.typeit.org/full/">full IPA keyboard</a> ins=
tead.
	</p>

	<ul id=3D"recommended-ipa-fonts">
	<li>
	After you copy text from the above box and paste it into your word process=
or or e-mail message,
	make sure you <b>choose a Unicode font with IPA symbols in your word proce=
ssor</b> or e-mail application.
	Otherwise, phonetic symbols may not display correctly.</li>
    <li>Recommended IPA fonts available on various platforms:
    <ul>
    <li><b>Windows</b>: <i>Segoe UI</i>, <i>Cambria</i>, <i>Calibri</i>, <i=
>Arial</i>, <i>Times New Roman</i>, <i>Tahoma</i> or <i>Lucida Sans Unicode=
</i> (incomplete)</li>
    <li><b>MacOS</b>: <i>Lucida Grande</i>, <i>Arial</i>, <i>Times New Roma=
n</i>, <i>Tahoma</i></li>
    <li><b>Linux</b>: depends on the distro, but <i>Linux Libertine</i>, <i=
>Linux Biolinum</i> and <i>DejaVu Sans</i> are good bets.</li>
    </ul>
    </li><li>
    If some of the symbols don=E2=80=99t display correctly, you=E2=80=99ll =
need to <a href=3D"https://www.typeit.org/help#fonts">download a third-part=
y IPA font</a>.
	</li><li>
	For help with transcribing, refer to Antimoon=E2=80=99s
	<a href=3D"http://www.antimoon.com/how/pronunc-soundsipa.htm">chart with I=
PA phonetic symbols,
	example words, and recordings</a> (make sure you read the footnotes).
	</li><li>
	Notes on specific symbols:

	<ul>
	<li>
	<span class=3D"char">=C9=AA=CC=88</span> can be used to represent a =E2=80=
=9Cweak <span class=3D"char">=C9=AA</span>=E2=80=9D (as in <i>poss<u>i</u>b=
le</i>), which
    usually sounds like something between <span class=3D"char">=C9=AA</span=
> and <span class=3D"char">=C9=99</span>.
	</li><li>
	<span class=3D"char">=CA=8A=CC=88</span> can be used to represent a =E2=80=
=9Cweak <span class=3D"char">=CA=8A</span>=E2=80=9D (as in <i>ed<u>u</u>cat=
ion</i>), which
    usually sounds like something between <span class=3D"char">=CA=8A</span=
> and <span class=3D"char">=C9=99</span>.
	</li><li>
    <span class=3D"char">t=CC=AC</span> can be used to indicate places wher=
e a =E2=80=9Cflap t=E2=80=9D is normally pronounced in American English. Fo=
r example,
    <i>letter</i> can be transcribed <span class=3D"char">/=CB=88let=CC=AC=
=C9=99=CA=B3/</span>.=20
    </li><li>
    <span class=3D"char"><sup>=C9=99</sup></span> can represent an optional=
 <span class=3D"char">=C9=99</span> (schwa) before a syllabic consonant,
    as in <i>butt<u>o</u>n</i>.
    </li><li>
    <span class=3D"char">=C9=9B</span>, <span class=3D"char">=C9=B9</span>,=
 <span class=3D"char">=C9=9A</span>, <span class=3D"char">=C9=9D</span>, <s=
pan class=3D"char">=C9=AB</span>
    and <span class=3D"char">=C9=BE</span> are not necessary in phonemic tr=
anscriptions, but are provided for those who might need them.
    </li>
	</ul>

	</li><li>
	If you=E2=80=99re learning other languages, check out my other online keyb=
oards, e.g.
	<a href=3D"https://russian.typeit.org/">Russian keyboard</a>, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://french.typeit.org/">French keyboard</a>, etc.
	</li>
	</ul>
